				\begin{document}$$\:UV\:Dose=Es\:Pf\:\left(1-R\right)\frac{L}{d+L}\frac{\left(1-{10}^{-UVA\:254\:d}\right)}{{UVA}_{254}\:d{ln}\left(10\right)}t$$\end{document}where, Es is the average UV intensity (mW/cm2), Pf is the unitless Petri factor, R is the reflectance at the air-water interface at 254 nm, L is the distance from the lamp centerline (cm), d is the depth of the suspension (cm), UVA 254 is the UV absorbance (UVA) at 254 nm (calculated by Eq. (3)), t is the exposure time (s). The optical light meter reading recorded an E_s value of 0.478 mW/cm2. The Pf factor was measured at 0.99, while the reflectance (R) was 0.025. The distance (d) was 0.52 cm, and the length (L) was 9.4 cm.

